# Architecture Rule — System Boundaries

Always preserve clear architectural boundaries.

## Main domains
1. Builder / Studio
2. Control Plane
3. Runtime Plane
4. Gateway / Exposure
5. Local Integration Plane

## Required service separation
- The frontend must not directly manage Kubernetes resources
- The control plane orchestrates deployments through a deployer service
- The runtime plane runs user workloads, not core SaaS admin logic
- Kong exposure must be managed through deployment metadata and gateway services
- OpenClaw integration must remain local-first and isolated from public cloud exposure

## Monorepo structure
Use this baseline structure:

apps/
  web-studio/
  desktop-builder/
  control-plane-api/
  deployer-service/
  runtime-agent/
  runtime-app-base/
  gateway-admin-api/
  openclaw-adapter/
  docs-site/

packages/
  ui/
  shared-types/
  sdk/
  deployment-spec/
  templates/
  auth/
  logging/
  telemetry/
  billing/
  secrets/
  tool-registry/
  model-providers/

infra/
  terraform/
  kubernetes/

## Architectural constraints
- Shared logic belongs in packages/, not duplicated in apps/
- API contracts must be typed and shared through packages/shared-types or sdk
- Deployment specs must be schema-driven
- Runtime workloads must be stateless by default unless explicitly designed otherwise
- Environment-specific behavior must be config-driven, not hardcoded

## Design principles
- API-first
- schema-first
- tenant-aware by design
- secure by default
- observable by default
- modular, replaceable services
